$\bar{v}=\frac{1}{\lambda}=R_H Z\left(\frac{1}{n_1^2}-\frac{1}{n_2^2}\right)$
In Balmer series $n_1=2 \& n_2=3,4,5 \ldots$... Last line of the spectrum is called series limit.
Limiting line is the line of shortest wavelength and high energy when $n_2=\infty$
$$
\begin{aligned}
\therefore \quad \bar{v}= & \frac{1}{\lambda}=\frac{R_H}{n_1^2}=\frac{3.29 \times 10^{15}}{2^2}=\frac{3.29 \times 10^{15}}{4} \\
& =8.22 \times 10^{14} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

According to de-Broglie wavelength equation,

$$

\lambda=\frac{h}{m v} \Rightarrow \lambda \propto \frac{1}{v}

$$

According to photoelectric effect,

$$

\begin{array}{l}

\mathrm{hv}-\mathrm{hv}_{0}=\frac{1}{2} \mathrm{mv}^{2} ; \mathrm{v}-\mathrm{v}_{0}=\frac{1}{2}=\frac{\mathrm{mv}^{2}}{\mathrm{~h}} \\

\mathrm{v}-\mathrm{v}_{0} \propto \mathrm{v}^{2} \\

\mathrm{v} \propto\left(\mathrm{v}-\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)^{1 / 2} \\

\therefore \quad \lambda \propto \frac{1}{\left(\mathrm{v}-\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)^{1 / 2}}

\end{array}

$$
